K-means clustering

K-means clustering (sometimes called Lloyds algorithm) works by attempting to group data into k disjoint groups of equal variance.

  • The means of the clusters are called centroids
  • The algorithm seeks to choose centroids that minimize inertia, or a within-cluster sum-of-squares criterion.
  • Makes the assumptions that clusters are convex (not open) and isotropic (globular, uniform in all directions)
  • Lower values of inertia are better, although it is not a normalized metric.
  • K-means will always converge, however this may be to a local minimum. This is highly dependent on the initialization of the centroids.
  • K-means generally performs well (quickly), converges, and is good with known numbers of clusters
  • On the downside, it may force clusters that dont apply to the data.

Lets create a smaller dataset with only the columns of interest for clustering.

# create subset
library(dplyr)
wholesale_sub <- 
  wholesale %>%
  select("Fresh":"Delicatessen")

Implementation is simple: use the kmeans function with centers parameter.

Notice we had to pre-specify the number of clusters (we picked 3 here).

# implement k-means clustering, n_clusers = 3
res_kmeans <- 
  kmeans(wholesale_sub,centers = 3)
# print the labels
res_kmeans$cluster

Warning: There is absolutely no guarantee of recovering a ground truth. First, choosing the right number of clusters is hard. Second, the algorithm is sensitive to initialization, and can fall into local minima.

Dont over-interpret clustering results!

Weaknesses of KMeans

  • Must choose number of clusters in advance
  • Sensitive to starting values
  • Wants regular-shaped geometry

Agglomerative Clustering

Agglomerative clustering is hierarchical clustering method using a bottom-up approach. Hierarchical methods work by successively splitting or joining clusters (like a plant taxonomy that splits plants into family, genus, species)

For the agglomerative method, each observation serves as its own cluster, and then clusters are merged or grown according to a defined metric. In the clustering methods provided, the agglomeration metric can be specified with the linkage parameter with choices ward, complete, or average. Below we try the method with both ward and average metrics, and compare the differences.

  • As with KMeans, the Ward approach seeks to minimize a sum-of-squared distance within clusters.
  • Complete minimizes maximum distances
  • Average minimizes mean distances
## Implement hierarchical clustering
clust_res <- 
  hclust(d=dist(wholesale_sub),method = 'ward.D')
plot(clust_res)

## Make labels using 'cut tree'
ag_lbl <- 
  cutree(clust_res,3)
## add variable to dataset
wholesale$aglbl <- 
  factor(ag_lbl)
# Create scatterplots
library(ggplot2)
ggplot(wholesale,
       aes(Fresh,Grocery, color = aglbl)) + 
  geom_point()

res1 <- 
  wholesale %>%
  group_by(aglbl) %>%
  summarise(across(Fresh:Delicatessen,sum))
res1

Evaluating clusters

As the Kmeans documentation mentions, choosing the number of clusters correctly is hard. Evaluating the success of a clustering algorithm presents challenges: there may be no ground truth to which to compare the cluster labels.

Silhouette Coefficient

Although some measures of evaluating clusters exist where ground labels are known, this is rarely the case in an unsupervised learning context. The silhouette coefficient is a measure of how well a cluster is defined. The silhouette coefficient is specified as the measure of the mean distance of a point to others in its class compared to the mean distance to the next nearest class.

  • From -1 for incorrect clustering and +1 for highly dense clustering.
  • Scores around zero indicate overlapping clusters.
  • The score is higher when clusters are dense and well separated
## start with 2 clusters and calculate the width
library(cluster)
kres <- kmeans(wholesale_sub,
               centers = 2)
kmeans_sil <- 
  silhouette(as.numeric(kres$cluster),
             dist = dist(wholesale_sub)^2) ## square since this is how kmeans works
# Summarize the result
summary(kmeans_sil)
## Silhouette of 440 units in 2 clusters from silhouette.default(x = as.numeric(kres$cluster), dist = dist(wholesale_sub)^2) :
##  Cluster sizes and average silhouette widths:
##         375          65 
##  0.82170527 -0.09115447 
## Individual silhouette widths:
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
## -0.6165  0.7150  0.8512  0.6869  0.8800  0.9017
# calculate mean sil width directly
mean(kmeans_sil[,'sil_width'])
## [1] 0.686851

Picking optimal number of clusters

We can use the silhouette coefficient to pick the optimal number of clusters. We do this by iterating over several fits and comparing the silhouette coefficients of each, and picking the maximum.

## calculate distance once:
wholesale_sub_dist <- 
  dist(wholesale_sub)^2
## write function to calculate the width
sil_func <- function(data,centers,dist){
  kres = kmeans(x =  data,
               centers = centers)
  kmeans_sil = silhouette(as.numeric(kres$cluster),
                          dist = dist)
  mean(kmeans_sil[,'sil_width'])
}
## apply function across range of clusters
sil_results <- 
  data.frame(n_clust=2:9,
           silwidth=sapply(2:9,function(x) sil_func(data = wholesale_sub,dist = wholesale_sub_dist,centers = x)))
sil_results
##   n_clust  silwidth
## 1       2 0.6868510
## 2       3 0.6491738
## 3       4 0.5467106
## 4       5 0.5315845
## 5       6 0.4662746
## 6       7 0.4703339
## 7       8 0.4666453
## 8       9 0.4651557
## Make a plot
ggplot(sil_results, aes(n_clust,silwidth)) + 
  geom_point() + geom_line()

Drawbacks to silhouette scores

  • Prefers compact shapes
  • Doesnt do well with complex shapes

Conclusion

  • In this lecture you have learned how to implement both kmeans clustering and heirarchical clustering approaches with R.
  • We also discussed different methods for assessing cluster performance, as well as methods for identifying the optimal number of clusters in a dataset.
  • recall that clustering is inherently exploratory in nature - since we do not have labels, we cannot test how well we are doing.
  • Also, recall there is no guarantee of getting meaningful results!
  • However, this is still a situationally useful technique for exploring subspaces of datasets.
